{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491565"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:52:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:52:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"983"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/983"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.5,0.1,0.02,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"983"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109969"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/983"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"983"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92327"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1263"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45785"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109969"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine medical check. He has no current complaints. His medical history includes hypertension, high cholesterol, gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, and heart failure. His regular medications are perindopril, amlodipine, metoprolol, atorvastatin, omeprazole, and spironolactone, which was commenced two weeks ago. He smokes five cigarettes per day and drinks one beer each night. He denies other drug use. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are three lipomata in his epigastrium, but no other abnormal fatty tissue. Another physical sign is readily visible (Image). His body mass index is 29 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for this incidental physical sign (not the lipomata)?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Obesity","Spironolactone","Alcohol intake","Omeprazole","Age-related"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis man has developed bilateral gynaecomastia. There are a variety of underlying causes of gynaecomastia in men (Image). The most likely explanation in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Eage-related\u003C/strong\u003E changes, which are common in older men and may be seen in up to one quarter of individuals in this age group. The gradual decline in testosterone and relative increase in oestrogen with age predispose to this finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E is a recognised cause of gynaecomastia, but this typically occurs after several months of therapy, not within two weeks of initiation. The short duration of use in this case makes it less likely to be the primary cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E can contribute to gynaecomastia through increased peripheral conversion of androgens to oestrogens in adipose tissue. However, this man has a body mass index in the overweight range and no other evidence of significant adiposity on examination, making this a less likely explanation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcohol intake\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with gynaecomastia in the context of chronic heavy use, due to its effects on liver metabolism and hormone balance. This man\u2019s consumption of one beer per night is considered moderate and unlikely to be the main cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmeprazole\u003C/strong\u003E and other proton-pump inhibitors have been rarely associated with gynaecomastia, but this is uncommon and usually requires prolonged use. In this scenario, age-related changes remain the most likely explanation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Age-related changes are the most common cause of gynaecomastia in older men.","Medication-induced gynaecomastia typically requires prolonged exposure before onset.","Moderate alcohol intake is less likely to cause gynaecomastia compared to chronic heavy use."],"references":["Cuhaci N, Polat SB, Evranos B, Esen I, Cakir B. Gynecomastia: Clinical evaluation and management. Indian J Endocrinol Metab. 2014 Mar-Apr;18(2):150\u20138.","Daniels J, Brickstock A, Charlton R. Gynaecomastia. BMJ. 2022 Nov 9;379:e069771."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92327"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"983"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18826"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18827"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18826"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/61f63991-3239-4248-9d5e-15998e789d63.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/61f63991-3239-4248-9d5e-15998e789d63.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":268,"height":215}},{"type":"media","id":"18827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18827"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/81b88c66-cf1c-4f3b-b284-c51ef0d8491f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8